Project Description
AI-Based Predictive Indoor Air Quality and Health Risk Monitoring System for Smart Homes
This project focuses on developing an intelligent smart home system that continuously monitors indoor air quality using multiple environmental sensors and analyzes the collected data using Artificial Intelligence (AI) to predict unhealthy conditions before they become dangerous.
In modern homes, indoor air pollution caused by gas leakage, smoke, poor ventilation, high humidity, rising CO2 levels, and dust accumulation can seriously affect human health. These problems often develop gradually and are difficult for people to notice manually. Traditional monitoring systems only provide simple alerts after dangerous levels are reached, but they cannot understand patterns, predict future risks, or identify the root cause of the problem.
To solve this problem, this project uses IoT sensors installed in different rooms of a smart home prototype made using acrylic sheets. Each room represents a real home environment such as kitchen, bedroom, living room, and bathroom. Multiple sensors like MQ-2 Gas Sensor, MQ135, DHT11, HC-SR501 PIR Motion Sensor, and window status sensors are used to collect real-time data related to gas levels, smoke presence, air quality, CO2 concentration, humidity, temperature, occupancy, and ventilation conditions.
The sensor data is collected through ESP32, which acts as the main controller of the system. The ESP32 sends this data to cloud storage or a database using Wi-Fi and IoT communication methods such as MQTT or ThingSpeak. This stored data becomes the dataset for AI analysis.
Artificial Intelligence is the main intelligence part of the project. Instead of simply showing sensor values, AI analyzes the relationships between multiple parameters and identifies patterns that are difficult for humans or normal microcontrollers to understand. For example, if CO2 levels are rising, the room is occupied, and windows remain closed, AI predicts poor ventilation. If gas concentration increases slowly during night hours while the kitchen is unoccupied, AI predicts a possible hidden gas leakage. If bathroom humidity remains high for long periods, AI predicts mold risk and unhealthy room conditions.
The AI model can also generate room-wise air quality scores, health risk predictions, pollution source identification, and ventilation recommendations. It helps users understand not only the current air quality but also future risks before they become serious. This makes the system predictive rather than reactive.
The final output of the project is displayed through dashboards, graphs, reports, and alerts showing room-wise air quality conditions, unhealthy trends, and predicted risks. This improves health, comfort, and safety inside smart homes.
The main objective of this project is to create an AI-integrated IoT smart home system that can intelligently analyze indoor air quality using multiple sensors and predict unhealthy environmental conditions in advance, making homes safer, healthier, and smarter.
